Documentation for "Aurora catcher" application 

1. Brief Description

Aurora Catcher is a neural networkвЂ“based application designed to detect aurora (northern or southern lights) in photographs of the night sky.

The application aims to assist both inexperienced users and experienced observers in recognizing auroras, especially when they are faint or easily confused with other sky phenomena like airglow, light pollution, or the Milky Way.

The core detection pipeline uses two models:

Model 1: Determines whether an aurora is present.
Model 2: If no aurora is detected, identifies the three most visually similar phenomena.

A mid layer orchestrates model execution and output processing, while a GUI layer presents results in a user-friendly interface.

2. Application architecture

The application is structured in three layers:

1. Presentation Layer (GUI / console)
Loads images.
Runs inference via a "Detect Aurora" button.
Displays results and allows saving output.
2. Mid Layer
Coordinates model execution.
Processes and translates model outputs for presentation.
3. Core ML Layer
Contains two convolutional neural networks (CNNs).
Model 1 specializes in aurora detection.
Model 2 identifies other phenomena only if Model 1 finds no aurora.

Pipeline Steps:

1. Load image.
2. Validate size and format.
3. Preprocess (resize, pad, normalize).
4. Run Model 1 (aurora detection).
5. Run Model 2 if needed.
6. Collect, translate, and display results.

3.Explanation for 2 model pipeline
Using a two-model pipeline ensures high precision for aurora detection:

Model 1 focuses solely on aurora recognition for maximal accuracy.
Model 2 provides secondary information on other phenomena, where precision is less critical.

This separation simplifies training and improves reliability compared to a single multi-label model.

4.Dataset
a) The dataset was created by collecting images from public sources, website and forum galleries, and personal galleries. Many of the images are protected by copyright, so it is
not possible to publish the full dataset. The images were used solely for training and validation purposes.
b)classes:
model1 : 2 classes (aurora, non aurora)
model2 : 7 classes (airglow, light pollution, lightning, milky way, NLC, twilight, zodiacal light)
c)dataset used for training both models contains 16333 images. 
d)preprocessing:
resize (128x128 for tunning hyperparameters, 256x256 for final training)
padding to square size,
normalization,
augmentation in training process: rotation (5 degrees, 20% data)
								  color jitter (brightness = 0.12, contrast = 0.12, 30% data)
								  gaussian noise (0.005, 20% data)
d) split: dataset has been split into three groups (train 70%, validation 15%, test 15%) and cca 90 images for hard validation check. 
This augmentation has been applied for both models.

